  <!-- WHAT THE MODEL DID NOT PREDICT -->
  <hr class="section-rule" />
  <div class="test-eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:var(--s2);">What the model did not predict</div>
  <h2 class="test-headline" style="font-size:clamp(20px,2.5vw,28px);margin-bottom:var(--s3);">Three outcomes were outside the model's scope. Being clear about this is part of how the model earns trust.</h2>

  <p class="n">A validation exercise is only credible if it honestly identifies what was not predicted alongside what was. Three categories of 2024 outcomes were outside scope.</p>

  <div class="verdict scope" style="margin-bottom:var(--s2);">
    <div class="verdict-icon" style="color:var(--text-tertiary);">○</div>
    <div class="verdict-body"><strong>Freight rate movements</strong>Container spot rates from Shanghai to Europe increased 256% at the February 2024 peak. The model captures the rerouting cost per voyage, not aggregate freight market pricing driven by fleet capacity effects. It answers who is exposed and what rerouting costs per voyage, not what the freight market will price in a tight vessel supply environment.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="verdict scope" style="margin-bottom:var(--s2);">
    <div class="verdict-icon" style="color:var(--text-tertiary);">○</div>
    <div class="verdict-body"><strong>Disruption timing and probability</strong>The model is conditional on a disruption occurring. It answers the question: if this corridor is disrupted, what is the exposure? It does not forecast which corridors will fail or when. Disruptions are exogenous events.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="verdict scope" style="margin-bottom:var(--s2);">
    <div class="verdict-icon" style="color:var(--text-tertiary);">○</div>
    <div class="verdict-body"><strong>Full container goods universe at Bab-el-Mandeb</strong>The model's Bab-el-Mandeb coverage is strong for bulk commodities and crude but narrower for containerised goods, which are carried in lower-confidence estimates. The total corridor exposure figure ($74.7B) is a floor on trade at risk, not a ceiling. Container tonnage at Suez fell 82% at the 2024 trough, a steeper proportional decline than the model's non-crude coverage captures.</div>
  </div>

